To load environment variables from a `.env` file to `application.properties` in Spring Boot, you can use the `dotenv` library. Here are the steps:

1. Add the `dotenv` library to your project's dependencies. You can do this by adding the following line to your `build.gradle` or `pom.xml` file:
```javascript
// Gradle
implementation 'io.github.cdimascio:dotenv-java:2.2.0'

// Maven
<dependency>
  <groupId>io.github.cdimascio</groupId>
  <artifactId>dotenv-java</artifactId>
  <version>2.2.0</version>
</dependency>
```
1. Create a `.env` file in the root directory of your project. This file should contain the environment variables you want to load into `application.properties`. For example:
```makefile
DB_USERNAME=myusername
DB_PASSWORD=mypassword
```
1. Add the following code to your `Application` class to load the environment variables from the `.env` file:
```java
import io.github.cdimascio.dotenv.Dotenv;

@SpringBootApplication
public class Application {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Dotenv dotenv = Dotenv.load();
    SpringApplication app = new SpringApplication(Application.class);
    app.setDefaultProperties(dotenv.getEntries());
    app.run(args);
  }
}
```
This code loads the environment variables from the `.env` file using the `Dotenv` class from the `dotenv` library. It then sets these variables as the default properties for the Spring Boot application using the `setDefaultProperties` method.

1. Now you can reference the environment variables in your `application.properties` file using the `${...}` syntax. For example:
```bash
spring.datasource.username=${DB_USERNAME}
spring.datasource.password=${DB_PASSWORD}
```
This will replace `${DB_USERNAME}` and `${DB_PASSWORD}` with the values from the `.env` file at runtime.

That's it! Your Spring Boot application should now be able to load environment variables from a `.env` file and use them in the `application.properties` file.
How do I add default values in the application.properties, when the .env file does not contain the key-value pair for the reference in application.properties?

To add default values in the `application.properties` file, you can use the Spring Boot `@Value` annotation with a default value. Here's an example:

Suppose you have an environment variable `DB_HOST` that you want to use in your `application.properties` file, but you also want to provide a default value in case the environment variable is not set. You can define a property in your `application.properties` file like this:
```bash
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://${DB_HOST:localhost}:3306/mydb
```
The `${DB_HOST:localhost}` syntax specifies a default value of `localhost` in case the `DB_HOST` environment variable is not set.

Then, in your Spring Boot application code, you can use the `@Value` annotation to inject the value of `spring.datasource.url` into a field:
```kotlin
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Value;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
public class MyComponent {
    @Value("${spring.datasource.url}")
    private String databaseUrl;

    // ...
}
```
If the `DB_HOST` environment variable is set, the `spring.datasource.url` property will be set to `jdbc:mysql://<DB_HOST_VALUE>:3306/mydb`. Otherwise, it will be set to `jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb` as per the default value specified in the `application.properties` file.
