```powershell
$registryPaths = @(
    "Registry::HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Office\16.0\Outlook\Profiles",
    "Registry::HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Office\16.0\Outlook\AutoDiscover"
)

foreach ($registryPath in $registryPaths) {
    if (Test-Path $registryPath) {
        Get-ChildItem -Path $registryPath -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | ForEach-Object {
            $currentProfile = $_.Name
            $newProfile = $currentProfile + "_old"
            Rename-Item -Path $_.PSPath -NewName $newProfile
            Write-Host "Renamed Outlook profile from $currentProfile to $newProfile"
        }
    } else {
        Write-Host "No Outlook profiles found at $registryPath"
    }
}
```
This script will search for the Outlook profile registry keys and rename the existing default profile by appending "\_old" to the profile name. When the user opens Outlook, the application won't find the default profile and will prompt them to create a new one. The old profile will still exist in the registry, but it will not be loaded automatically.

Keep in mind that this script affects the currently logged-in user. If you need to run the script for all users on a machine, you can either run it in the context of each user or remotely execute it using tools like PsExec.

